The denominator 7 suggests roots of the form of the 7th roots of unity, $$z^7 = 1, z\ne 1$$. We observe that all the cosines can be found from manipulating real parts of these roots</think> <answer>Let $z=e^{2\pi i/7}$, a 7th root of unity.  Then the 7th roots of unity satisfy $z^7-1=0$, and by factoring we have \begin{align*}z^7-1 &= (z-1)(z^6+z^5+\cdots+z+1) \\ &= 0.\end{align*} Now canceling the zero, $z^6+z^5+\cdots+z+1=0$.  Then \[1+z+\cdots+z^6 =0.\]  Then \begin{align*}2+2z^2+2z^4 &= (1+z+\cdots+z^6)+(z+z^3+\cdots+z^6)+z^2 \\ &= 1+2z+2z^2+\cdots+2z^6 + z^2 \\ &= (1+z^2)(1+z+\cdots+z^6) \\ &= 0.\end{align*} Then $z^2=-1$, or $2z^2=-2$, and then \begin{align*}2+2z^3+2z^6+ 2z^2 &= 2+2z^3+2z^5-2 \\ &= 2z^3+2z^5 \\ &= 2z^3(1+z^2) \\ &= -2z^3.\end{align*}  Thus, we have found that $-z^3=1+z^2+z^4+z^5+z^6$.


